{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_dumas_ver01/data/sn84031081/00415627828/1921010101/0014.xml":{"full_text":"FOUR\nITOuqutfqUg Morhuig Jmfffiair Safurday, January T, 1921.'\nPAGINATION INCORRECT\nONEVILLISTAIS\nJ\nback\nDEMI\nN fJEW CHARGES\nSTRIKE PROBLEM HAS\nBEEN SOLVED ON THE\nPENNSY ROAD, BELIEF\nSpecial Cflrrenwndenca to The Journal.)\nSanta Fe, Dec. 81. Rafael Bus-\namente. one of the sixteen Villls-\nng, has been taken to Demlng for\nrraignment in a justice of the\neace court on the charge of mur-\n:er.\nFour deputy sheriffs from Luna\nounty arrived here to take the en\nIre sixteen to Demlng, but it was\nnutid that Judge Haymond R.\ntyan's order would hold the other\nifteen In the penitentiary until\nHeir trial.\nBustamente, however, had not\neen Indicted for the murder of\naore than one of the Columbus\naid victims and owing to that fact\nid not come under the district\nidge'a Jurisdiction. The Judge\nould not order his being held In\nie penitentiary for safekeeping.\nBustamente probably will be held\nt Deming two weeks until his\nreliminary hearing has been held.\nfeMhen will be held for the grand\niry, bringing him within the dis-\nrlct court's jurisdiction, or dis-\nharged as not guilty.\nThe lone Villista will be ar-\naigned on a complaint, filed in\nhe Justice of the peace court by\nhe district attorney charging him\nith murder.\nSTARR TO GET JOB\nAS PEN LIBRARIAN\nSpecial Correspondence to The Journal.)\nSanta Fe, Dec. 81. Jesse O.\ntarr, now a \"lifer\" as the result\nf the commutation of his sentence\nrom death to imprisonment ror\nfe for the murder of Sheriff\n)wight B. Stephens, Luna county,\nag been given a job as the result\nf his new classification.\nAs a condemned man Starr\n.asn't allowed to have any Job ex-\npt that of sitting in his cell wait-\n5 for the supreme 8 court aeci\nn on his appeal. His sentence\nSed for hanging by the neck un\n\"3ead and not Imprisonment at\nI 3- labor and. although he un-\nbubtedly would have preferred\norking, prison officials couldn't\nike the chance. Like other men\nnder the shadow of the scaffold,\nwas kept in close confinement\nxceptwhen he took his daily ex-rcise.\nStarr's lob is that of librarian.\nle was wounded in the battle be\nwecn the sheriffs posse and the\nscaped prisoners, of whom he was\nne, and permanently crippled. He\nan't walk without crutches and\nhat accounts for his being as\nsigned to a \"desk\" Job.\nAccording to prison officials\ntarr was as pleased as a boy out\nf school for vacation when he was\niven something to do.\n'1.X\nDOG MISSED FROM AUTO PARTY\nAND SEARCH FOR ANIMAL SHOWS\nROSWELL ATTORNEY MISSING TOO\nr -i\n(SPECIAL CORRESPONDENCE TO MORNING JOURNAL)\nHoswell, N. M.. Dec. 31.\n\"Harry, where is your dog?\"\nHad it not been for the per\ntinent question fired point\nblank by Judge Charles R,\nBrlce at Attorney Harry C.\nMaynard a searching party\nmight have been necessary to\nrescue Attorney J. Charles Gil\nbert from the sand dunes and\ncactus flats of somewhere in\neastern New Mexico.\nIt all came about this way:\nJudge Brlce and Attorneys H.\nC. Maynard and J. C. Gilbert\nhad formed a hunting party\neast of the city and coming\nback Charlie was comfortably\nplaced in the rear seat, while\nHarry Maynard had his hand\non the throttle and Judge\nBriee was watching the road.\nThe dog everyone knows\nHarry Maynard's dog was\nalong for no better reason than\nHarry was, and when the re\nturn journey was begun the\ndog was on the running tooard\nuntil and up to the time of the\nstartling discovery made by\nJudge Brice. In looking about\nfor the dog the two made the\ndiscovery that Charlie was\nmissing. A long look back\ndown the road as far as the\neye could reach even in the\nhigh, clear atmosphere of New\nMexico revealed nothing, not\neven the dog.\nThere was nothing to do but\nfor the two to retrace their\nsteps in search of their fellow\nbarrinter, and the dog, of\ncourse. Miles and miles be\nhind, they found the dog, and\neven further toward the east\nthey found Charlie, like the\nhero of Gray's Elegy, \"Home\nward plodding his weary way.\"\nIt was all simple when the\nstory was told. There was just\na little bump in the road and\nthere was no top on the car\nto receive the impact of Char\nlie's body as it rose high In the\nair.\nThe trip home, at least the\nremainder of it, was quite\nsuccessfully made and neither\nCharlie or the dog are feeling\nany bad effects of their experience.\nTEXAS LEADS 11\nLYNCHING BEES\nFOR YEAR 10\nIn Germany the University\nBerlin has 16,000 students.\nof\nHORSES ON WAY TO\nCAVALRY TROOPS OF\nSTATE AT CARLSBAD\n(SpeeJal Correependenee to The Jonnml.)\nSanta Fe, Dec. 81. The first\nshipment of horses for the First\nNew Mexico cavalry is on the way\nfrom Phoenix, Ariz., according to\nAdjutant General James Baca. The\nhorses will go to, Troop B at Carls\nbad.\nThe shipment includes thirty-\ntwo trained mounts which have\nbeen in service in the First\nUnited Statts cavalry and consti\ntutes Troon B's full allotment. The\ntroop's stables have been built al\nready and its equipment, consisting\nchiefly or rifles and uniforms,\nprobably has been received by this\ntime. The adjutant general's office\nwas Informed some time ago that\nthe equipment had been shipped.\nThe troop is one of the two al\nready organized in the state and is\ncommanded by Capt. Fred M.\nWest. The other troop is stationed\nat Albuquerque.\n\"G cup\nI u j\n(4 Good at any hour of tht day\njBaker's Cocoa i\njis especially good in the\nevening a short time be\nfore retiring. Its flavor\nlis delicious, its aroma\nfmost attractive, and it\nlis conducive to restful\nf sleep without being in\nI r r.i j.\nlany sense 01 tne woru, a\nnarcotic. Ab\nsolutely pure\nand wholesome.\nj\nBOOKLET OF CHOICE\nRECIPES SENT FREE\nWalter Bakr&Colld.\nMTABUIHED l'OO-D0(lClHMiB.n53\nI,\nJ\nSMri'Troubles\nbij Daily Use of\nCutieura\nMake Cutieura Soap\nand Ointment your\nevery -day toilet prep\narations. Bathe with\nthe Soap and hot\nwater on rising and\nretiring, using plenty\nof Soap, best applied\nwith the hands.\nSmear any signs of\npimples, redness or\nroughness with the\nJintment and let it remain five\nusutes before bathing. Finally\n,ust on a few grains of the tx-\niflruiaitely perfumed Cutieura Tal\ncum, it takes the place of other\nt lerf umr far the Vin\n.t-\nWOMEN CAN'T SIT ON\nJURIES IN THE STATE\n(Special Corrmpondene. to The Journal.)\nSanta Fe, Dec. 31. There's\nstill one thing lacking to placing\nwomen on equality with the men\nin Now Mexico, although they now\nhave the ballot, and that's the fact\nthat they cannot serve as jurors.\nAssistant Attorney General Har\nry S. Bowman, replying to a re\nquest for an opinion today, cited\nSection 1, Chapter 23, Session Laws\nof 1917, which says that only-male\ncitizens, otnerwise qualified as to\nage, residence and mental condi\ntion, can act as twelve good men\nand true at court trials.\nThe women, of course, can't hold\nelective state offices, but the com\ning legislature will submit a con\nstitutional amendment changing\nthat. Even then, however, they\nwon't be able to serve as jurors,\nunless the legislature amends the\nstatute which bars them.\nSince it's only a statute it can\nbe changed at any time, when the\nlegislature is in session, but so far\nno demand from the women for\namendment has ben heard at the\nstate house. It's possible they don't\nwant equality to that extent.\nPROCLAMATION\nWhereas, it Is provided by law\nthat Justices of the Peace and Con\nstables shall be elected on the sec\nond Monday in. January of every\nother year and that elections for\nsuch purposes shall be held in each\nodd numbered year, now therefore:\nIt is proclaimed and ordered by\nthe Board of County Commission\ners of Bernalillo County, New Mex\nico, that an election will be held in\nsaid county on Monday, the 10th\nday of January, 1921, and that the\nobject of said election Is to elect\none justice of the peace and one\nconstable in each and every pre\ncinct of said county.\nAnd it is further proclaimed and\nordered that said election will be\nheld in the various precincts and\nelection districts of said Bernalillo\ncounty at the following named\nplaces, to-wit:\nPrecinct No. 1, San Jose, at\nhouse of Melqulades Sanches,\nPrecinct No. 2. Del Rio, at house\nof Epifanio 'Chaves.\nPrecinct No. 3, Alameda, at\nhouse of Maximo Perea.\nPrecinct No, 4. Ranchos de Al\nbuquerque, at school house.\nPrecinct No. 6, Barelas. at of\nfice of justice of the peace.\nPrecinct No. 6, Los Padillas, at\nhouse of Mariano Padilla.\nPrecinct No. 7, San Antonto, at\nhouse of Charles Kemp,\nPrecinct No. S. Los Grlegoa, at\nhouse of Gregorlo Garcia,\nPrecinct No, 9. Ranchos de\nAtrisco, at house David J. Armijo.\nPrecinct No. 10, Escobosa, at\nhouse oi cayetano Alaerete,\nPrecinct No. 11, Pajarito, at\nhouse of Cleofag Sanches.\nPrecinct No. 12, Albuquerque, at\nCity Hall.\nPrecinct No, 13. Old Albuquer\nque, at Society hall,\nPrecinct No. 14. San Ignacio, at\nhouse of Nicolas Herrera,\nPrecinct No. 15. Santa, Barbara,\nat Archuleta s hall.\nPrecinct No. 22. La ffljera, at\nhouse ot Jose Dominguez.\nPrecinct No. 23, San Antonlto, at\nhouse of Manuel G. y Lopez,\nPrecinct No. 26, Albuquerque, at\n200 West Gold avenue, office of\nNational Investment company.\nPrecinct No, 28, Atrisco, at house\nof Deslderio Carabajal,\nPrecinct No. 34, Chilili, at house\nof Anastaclo Gutierrez.\nPrecinct No. 85. Duranes, at Jus\ntice of peace office.\nAnd it Is further proclaimed and\nordered that the polls of said elec\ntion shall be opened on said 10th\nday of January, 1912, from 9\nO'clock in the forenoon until 6\no'clock in the afternoon of said\nday.\nBy order ot the Board of County\nCommissioners.\nM. K. WTLDER,\nAttest: Chairman.\nNESTOR MONTOTA, Clerk.\nGrand Rapids, Mich., Is the only\ncity-in the union that maintains\npublic art school. Massachusetts\nis the only state that supports au\nW Kim\nDIRECTOR OF MINES'\nBUREAU RESIGNS POST\n(Br The Amioeiatod Preaa.)\nWashington, Dec. 31. Frederick\nG. Cottrell, director of the bureau\nof mines, presented his resignation\nto President Wilson today through\nSecretary Payne of the interior de\npartment. Director Cottrell before\ncoming to the bureau as assistant\ndirector in September, 1919, re\nsided in Oakland, Calif.\nSecretary Payne, in presenting\nthe resignation, recommended that\nH. Foster Dain, also of California,\nbe appointed to the vacancy.\nMiss Eleanor McDougall, head\nof the Women's Christian College\nof Madras, is now in America\nspeaking on the higher education\nof women in India.\nNumber in Nation Decreased\nAs Compared With 1919,\nAccording to Report Made\nBy Tuskegee Institute.\n(Br The AMociated Frem)\nTuskogee, Ala., Dec. 31. Lynch\ning.? were less numerous in 1920\nthan in 1919, according to records\ncompiled at Tuskogee institute and\nmade public today. Sixty-one per\nsons, including eight white men,\ntvere, lynched this year as compared\nwith eighty-three last year and\nsixty-four in 1918, the statement\nsaid.\nIn fifty-six instances in 1920\nofficers of the law prevented lynch\ningB, the report showed, ten of\nthese instances being in northerr\nand forty-six in southern states.\nArmed force was used to repel\nwould-be lynchers in fourteen cas\nes and in four of these, mobs were\nfired upon, seven of the attackers\nhaving been killed and a number\nwounded.\nOf the sixty-one persons lynched,\nfifty-two were in the south and\nnine In the north and west. One\nwas a negro woman. Eighteen ne\ngroes were lynched charged with\nhaving attacked white women. The\noffenses charged against the white\nmen were:\nMurder, five; insulting women,\none; \"no charges except being a\nforeigner,\" one; white officers of\nthe law, one.\nOffenses charged against ne-1\ngroes lynched included:\nMurder, five; killing landlords,\nsix; Insulting women, two; knock-,\ning down guard (escaping from\nchain gang and then returning and\nsurrendering), two, and one each\nof the following: Jumping labor\ncontract, cutting man in fight, \"for\nreceiving stay of death sentence be\ncause another confessed crime,\"\npeeping through window at wom\nan, \"insisting on voting.\"\nct jtrosporous\n!r r3sV \"1\nm sv.pvbim m wet\nPROSPERITY AND HAPPINESS for\nJ- the New Year to all our friends and\nprospective friends, and may there be\nmusic in the homes of all those whom we\nknow arid those whom we do not know,\nthroughout this New Year is the wish\nof the\nAlbuquerque Music Store\nPhone 778\n311 West Central Albuquerque, N. M.\nBy states, lynchings \"occurred. s\nfollows\nTexas, ten; Georgia, nine; Mis\nsissippi, Alabama and Florida, sev\nen each; Minnesota, North Caro\nlina, Oklahoma and California,\nthree each; Arkansas, Kansas, Illi\nnois, Kentucky, Missouri, Ohio,\nSouth Carolina, Virginia and West\nVirginia, one each.\n:;'S0f the\" 40,000 words in, the. Eng\nlish dictionary, no more than 10.\n000 words are used; spoken Eng\nlish amounts to less than 5,000\nwords.\nMississippi has fifty agricultural\nhigh schools with an enrollment of\n7,000 pupils. Each school has a\nfarm ranging from 60 to 100 acres.\nWARNING\nI Unless you see the name \"Bayer\" on tablets, you are\nnot getting genuine Aspirin prescribed by physicians for\n21. years, and proved safe by millions. Say \"Bayer\"J\nSAFETY FIRST! Accept only an \"unbroken package\" of\ngenuine \"Bayer Tablets of Aspirin,\" which contains proper direc\ntions for Headache, Earache, Toothache, Neuralgia, Colds, Rheu\nmatism, Neuritis, Lumbago, and pain generally. Strictly American!\nHandy tin boxes of 12 tablets cost but a few cents Larger packages.\nAaplrln It the trad mark of Bayer Manufacture of Monoacetlcacldeater of Ballcyllcaeld\n-:a';jjjj\nRing out the old, ring in the new,\n.Ring, happy bells, across the snow;\nThe year is going, let him go\nRing out the false, ring in the true.\nRing out old shapes of foul disease,\nRing out the narrowing lust of gold\nRing out the thousand wars of old,\nRing in the thousand years of peace.\nTennyson.\nPhone 520\n114 \"West Central\nmm -Pm\nHnAouteke\nItttheNc\nEXPRESSING OUR appreci\nation ,and thanking you\" for.\nyour remembrance during the\npast year, we wish you a Happy,\nProsperous' New .Year.\nGeo. C. Scheer Furniture Company\n315-317 South Second 314-316 South Second\nPhone 431\nTING&\nDIM AT THE\nPULLMAN CAFE\nSPECIAL NEW YEAR TURKEY j\nDINNER TODAY,\nPARTICULAR PEOPLE EAT AT THE\nPOLLMAII CAFE\nJ. M. HANNA, Proprietor\nPhone 759. 118 West Central\nGLASS, PAINT.\nCEMENT. PLASTEH\nA1XUQUERQUE LUMBER COMFAWX\nLUMBER\nIn extending our best wishes to the people of Albuquerque and Newf Mexico for a\nhappy and prosperous New Year, we offer something more than a mere expression\nof good will, because it is our purpose during 1921 to do some very definite things in\nthe conduct of New Mexico's largest department store which will serve to increase the\ncomfort and happiness and to enhance the prosperity of those who are now and who\nwill become our patrons.\nIn October, 1920, Rosenwald's observed the Tenth\nAnniversary of the present establishment. We cele\nbrated that anniversary by inaugurating a new\npolicy of greater volume of sales at reduced mar\ngins of profit. In doing this we were not influenced\nby the approaching trend of prices downward, but\nentirely by the fact that our business had grown to\nthe point where this new policy had become pos\nsible. It was one of our goals, toward which we\nhad been striving earnestly for ten years; the time\nwhen the growth of our business would permit us\nto further increase volume of sales and further re\nduce our margins of profit; making, as we believed\nand are now convinced, equally for our own pros\nperity and for the benefit of our patrons.\nThus, by inaugurating the new Tenth Anniversary\npolicy of more volume in sales and closer margins\nof. profit, we not only gave to you, our patrons,\nfinal proof of the purpose of this store to pioneer\nin every advance in retail merchandising in Albu\nquerque and to lead the way in better service to the\npublic, but we also anticipated by a number of\nweeks those general price reductions which all\nmerchants throughout the country later found it\nnecessary to make.\nIn 1921 we propose to further broaden and strength\nen the Tenth Anniversary policy. The gratifying\ngrowth of our business during 1920 insures us of a\ncontinued increase in the good will felt toward\nRosenwald's by the people we serve. It insures us\nthe further increase in volume for the New Year\ntoward which we have \"been working. And these\nassurances, in turn, make it possible for us, in every\ndepartment, to further reduce our margins so that\nevery patron, in whatever department, and io what\never purchase, will feel In actual savings the def\ninite results of our efforts. j,\nWe share none of the pessimism felt by some with\nregard to the business outlook in 1921. We have\nan abiding faith in America and in the wisdom of\nthe American government to meet and pass safely\nthrough every crisis of financial and industrial ad\njustment. We believe that the crisis of the present\nadjustment has been safely passed and that the\npendulum of the national prosperity is again about\nto swing upward.\nWe make no rash and glittering promises of enor\nmous drops in prices during the coming year, be\ncause our careful analysis of trade conditions, in\ndustry and available stocks convinces us that no\nsuch further radical reductions will occur. Should\nany such further reductions in prices take place you\nmay rest assured that Rosenwald's will be found\nleading the way in meeting those prices.\nIn the meantime, firm in our faith in the business\noutlook, and equally firm in our confidence in the\nsound basis of our new policy of volume of business\nand narrowed margins of profit, we have bought\ngenerously for 1921; every department has-been\nserved upon the basis of a noatble increase in the\ndemands upon it, and the prices at which the mer\nchandise will be offered, will insure that increase in\nthe demands.\nTherefore, in extending to you our New Year's\nGreetings, we extend to you also an assurance of\nincreased service in every department of this store,\nwhich we are prepared to demonstrate to you as an\neffort making for your comfort, convenience and\neconomy; and hence, for your greater happiness\nand prosperity, i\nWe heartily appreciate the splendid patronage you have given us during 1920 and we\nearnestly solicit its continuance during 192 1, assuring you that no effort will be\na. iRwred by. us to just jfjr your confidence.\n'A\n4.!', i\nIfclllllMMfFil!:\n;i u uvu u u v v -,vyj u vyj u\nmmiwi ,i m. m r- 1","height":"27140","width":"19876"}}
